Informed Consent:
SAINT LOUIS UNIVERSITY

Recruitment Statement for Research Participation

 
1. Jack Friedrich, Saint Louis University Psychology Graduate Student, is inviting you to participate in this research study.



2. The title of this study is More than Perverse Incentives: Questionable Research Practices in the Organizational Sciences. The purpose of this study is to better understand research practices used in the organizational sciences and their relationship with various social norms and experiences of publication pressure.



3. Your participation in this study will involve completing an online survey that will take approximately 15 minutes to complete. The survey will ask about your experiences related to various research practices and with publication pressure.



4. To be eligible for this study, you must be a researcher in the organizational sciences, have conducted quantitative research that involves null hypothesis significance testing, and be at least 18 years of age.



5. The risks to you as a participant are minimal. These include loss of confidentiality, boredom/fatigue, loss of time, and potential discomfort in answering questions about yourself. To minimize risk, your responses will be anonymous (no identifying information will be collected), the questions will not assess illegal or sensitive topics, and you are free to skip any questions you are uncomfortable responding to.



6. The results of this study may be published in scientific research journals or presented at professional conferences. However, your name and identity will not be revealed and your record will remain anonymous.



7. Participation in this study will not benefit you directly. Your participant may benefit others by helping us understand the relationships between publication pressure, social norms, and various research practices in the organizational sciences.



8. You can choose not to participate. If you decide not to participate, there will not be a penalty to you or loss of any benefits to which you are otherwise entitled. You may withdraw from this study at any time.



9. If you have questions about this research study, you can email Jack Friedrich at jack.friedrich@slu.edu. If you have questions about your rights as a research participant, you can call the Saint Louis University Institutional Review Board at 314-977-7744 and reference IRB #34401.

By clicking "I agree," you are consenting to the conditions described above.

HARKing V._4: Dr. Patel is conducting research on the relationship between psychological safety and employee voice behaviors. Her planned analyses yield significant effects that are consistent with the literature but not particularly novel. During an exploratory analysis she discovers a significant, unexpected effect for certain groups in her dataset that is much more compelling than her original hypotheses and if it were the focus of the paper would likely strengthen the impact and publishability of her paper, particularly in a top-tier journal. In her place, would you: - 4
Optional Stopping V._4: Dr. Garcia is conducting a lab study with two conditions. He is randomly assigning members to a leadership style and examining the impact of the style on team performance. The study is expensive and time-intensive to run. He preregistered that he would collect data from 40 teams, but he is running analyses after every fifth team’s data collection and obtains a significant result after collecting data from the 30th team. In his place, would you: - 4
Hide Imputation V._1: Dr. Anderson finally finishes data collection for his study on factors contributing to burnout at work for a hard-to-study population, but unfortunately responses to many of his key variables have very high degrees of missingness. He decides to fill missing values in his dataset with estimated values, using a very common imputation method, but the degree of missingness in his data is slightly higher than recommended for use with this method. In his place, would you: - 1
Switch Analysis V._1: Dr. Thompson is conducting research on the relationship between job satisfaction, work engagement, and the outcome of employee turnover. Upon running her analyses, Dr. Thompson is surprised to discover that the analysis she had originally chosen and that she believes is most appropriate for her data, a multiple logistic regression, returns a null effect. There are, however, several other plausible analyses she could run. In her place, would you: - 1
Selective Cov. V. _1: Dr. Lewis is running the analyses for her study on remote work. Her regression model includes a number of covariates that she hypothesized would be related to experiences of remote work, but she discovers that some of the covariates’ effects on experiences of remote work are non-significant. In her place, would you: - 1
Exclude Selective V._1: Dr. Walker is studying the influence of personality traits on work-life balance. He obtains a non-significant correlation of r = .21 and p = .054 for what he believed would be his strongest result. After this result, he examines the scatterplot for the correlation and notices that a few datapoints that he could justify as outliers are preventing his results from reaching statistical significance. In his place, would you: - 1
Underreport Res. V._1: Dr. Xu is studying the impact of job characteristics on employee strengths use. Some of her analyses yield negligible, non-significant effects. After reviewing her results, she believes the analyses that demonstrated null effects may not be relevant to the story she is telling in her planned publication. In her place, would you: - 1
Omit non-sig. V._1: Dr. Taylor runs multiple, well-powered studies testing hypotheses consistent with a very well-established theory of work motivation. Reviewing his results, Dr. Taylor is surprised to find that the results of some of his studies are non-significant and inconsistent with the theory. In his place, would you: - 1
Selective Outcome V._1: Dr. King is applying for an academic job a few years after graduation and decides to publish her dissertation on the impact of workplace bullying on worker outcomes such as job turnover, satisfaction, and engagement. Several outcome variables in her original dissertation study were non-significant, and upon revisiting the topic in her dissertation, she deems them less relevant to the topic than she did when originally conducting the study. In her place, would you: - 1
Round P-value V._1: The result of Dr. Bell’s key hypothesis test in his most recent research project examining predictors of organizational citizenship behaviors is right above the threshold for statistical significance at p = .053. He believes the result indicates there is an effect but worries that a technically non-significant finding will result in a rejection at the journal that best fits the study’s topic. In his place, would you: - 1
Hide Problems V._1: Dr. Carter’s paper exploring predictors of employee experiences of inclusion is ready for submission for publication when she discovers a data quality issue that could impact some of her conclusions and likelihood of publication; most of her participants gave inconsistent responses in her online data collection. She could recollect data, but it would require more additional time and resources than she has available. However, she worries that disclosing the issue would impact her likelihood of publication. In her place, would you: - 1

Feedback: Interesting study. I think one aspect that hasn't come up is the difficulty of publishing papers that aren't parsimonious in their presentation. Reviewers don't like noisy stories, so we often omit variables that aren't important to that story. I have a tendency to report too much but I have many senior colleagues who exert pressure in collaborations to "clean up" the story. Few journals allow the space and incentives to do real science rather than storytelling.

Feedback: The research omits (ironically) a very important consideration. The reason for only reporting significant results is not driven by the malice or lack of ethics of the researcher, but rather by the fact that the journal (mostly) wants to see significant results only. Thus, not out of unethical reasons, the researcher constrained by 5000 to 8000 words journal limitations, only reports on the methods and results that were significant.

Feedback:
I wanted to expand on this one: "Reporting a set of results as the complete set of analyses when other analyses were also conducted" -- I always report the results that were preregistered. But in addition, I conduct more robustness checks and exploratory analyses. Some of those may end reported in an appendix/online supplement, or they may lead to a follow-up study -- or they may not be interesting enough to report. In some cases, I have used the results of analyses only in response letters to reviewers. Ultimately, there are many exploratory questions one could ask, and I make the data publicly available for people who want to play with the data themselves.

Similarly with not reporting studies. In some cases, reviewers ask for studies to be redone with some changes. Occasionally, the original version is worth including in an online supplement. But in nearly all cases in my experience, the results remained unchanged and the old version gets dropped from the paper to avoid being repetitive.

Feedback: In economics research, we value being open about the data analysis and data handling: for example, we use several different types of analysis to show the results are robust, and when estimating a regression model, we do that with several sets of covariates, again to show the robustness. Feedback: Sometimes regarding your possible answers, there is no "black and white" category to decide. For example, when methods did not yield significant results, another option is to sell the results in a "short paper" or "research in progress paper" at an academic conference. While academic conferences are not that established in business and social sciences, in business information systems there are a lot of established (and also internationally ranked) conferences, where some parts of the results (e.g., from a journal article to be published) can be published. However, in my humble opinion, academic pressure and the rather corrput system based on "who you know" in conjunction with the rather formal ranking of journals/publications puts more pressure on PhD candidates, as quantity seems to be more important than quality, ultimately leading to the pressure to publish or perish. In addition, the review culture in major journals is quite bad (and there are also a lot of articles online about this issue), as science is more about publications and reputation, rather than focussing on epistemological processes.

Feedback:
Although most of the behaviors are clear questionable research practices, some of them can be used in publications as long as you are transparent about them (e.g., using additional analyses) and also report the original results. I was somewhat missing such options when answering the items.

Finally, I would avoid using the social desirability scale that you used at the end as people do not interpret such scales as absolute statements. They generally approach them as if they are measuring personality traits and you just do not know at what level of agreement they decide to switch from "true" to "false". To be clear, even people who are agreeable with others who are annoying in most of the cases likely choose true to the statement rather than they choose false if they at one point in their life have not been agreeable.

Best of luck with the project.

Feedback:
in practise, we often estimate different variations of our baseline model to probe the robustness of our results. these alterantivies to baseline are rarely reported in detail - at least if they conform to the main story of the paper. the papers are too long already so reporting all variations to baseline as robustness checks usually does not make sense. of course, this leaves more room for file drawer effects and strategic omission. 

in general, i am optimistic about pre-registering even non-experimental studies.

Feedback: The questions about not reporting all results are confusing. It takes months in my discipline to make sure the data is free from error and initial data analyses will direct towards errors. Sometimes the researcher has inappropriate theory and unexpected results will draw attention to this. A researcher might change their statistical techniques if they adopted inappropriate ones initially.  Non significant results could be interesting. You might leave out non significant results because their are  highly correlated with other variables and that gives multicollinearity if you are using multivariate analyzes. You might not know this until you start analyzing the data. Research is a major benefit to society so it is important to show integrity. That does not mean reporting all results as the paper must be contained in about 50 pages. Gaining publication should not be the overreaching outcome. It should be about producing high quality research that benefits society. Some of my data sets are 15000+.

Feedback:
Many of the scenarios were a bit simplified lacking context: For example reporting complete analyses should not be an ideal. The first step in any project should be data exploration and I do not think that all the scatterplots need to be reported, for example. Similarly, when using complex analysis techniques such as SEM you might need to manually specify starting values. To find good starting values, doing a simpler analysis first is a good practice. Likewise, you might want to diagnose a complex model by checking if you get similar results using a simpler model. I do not think that all these need to be reported.

The same applies to selective reporting. If I were to write a dissertation that contains 50 models, but I know that In a journal article I can only fit 10 models, then I must report the reports selectively to hit the page limit. It is always possible to link to the dissertation for the full set of analyses, but probably most readers of the journal article would not read it...

Another contextual issue that the survey omitted is pressure from the family. Some academics have spouses in academia and publish together. It is really hard to object to data mining that your significant other does even if you would not engage in those practices when first-authoring a paper.

Feedback:
1. There are situations, when you collect more data, e.g. 2-3 studies in one data collection. In this event, you don't report the variables as they were from another study. But the reason is the funding when people have to combine data collections. Is it a bad practice? According to your questions - it might be.

2. It depends on what you understand as covariates. If they are part of the hypotheses - they should be reported. But if you have several control variables (usual suspects like age and gender, but also experience, experience in a particular firm, experience in a particular field, education, etc) you may decide that reporting all covariates just overloads paper with unnecessary information. So, regarding your question on covariates - I would say "it depends".

4. Regarding moving to other methods. You usually start with a correlation, then ANOVA, and then move to Multivariate analysis, where you can add more control variables. I don't know studies where people jumped into analysis before running other analyses like outliers check, missing variables check, correlation, ANOVA, etc. Yet, the significance may change if you add more controls or if you switch from ANOVA to coding a variable as a dummy and run a regression. The procedures are slightly different. The vinal p-values will differ but only slightly. I am not sure you meant this practice, when you asked the question about switching between methods.

Good luck with your research! And, btw, my colleagues don'T show me their analyses or do it seldom. So, the question about percentage of scholars who engage...  is very vague, imho.

Feedback: Some of the questions were hard to answer. I decided to answer them in the context that I am used to in my discipline, namely, that studies (especially those to be published in top journals) need to be preregistered and come with replication packages. Such studies also allow for exploratory analysis and results, which are defined as anything that has not been preregistered. Eventually, everything that has been preregistered needs to be reported. But it is allowed to add (or not to add) anything beyond the preregistration, marked as exploratory. Readers then can interpret these results as such. Given that preregistrations and replication packages are public, the process is transparent. Because of replication packages, it is also impossible to "mis-report p-values" or "simulate data without indication". You either have to forge your data (which is obviously crossing the line, I guess everybody agrees on that), or such practice would be detected and have consequences, often already during the publication process (thus in fact decreasing your chances of publication).

Feedback: I think that there is a meaningful difference between fabricating data/results and paring down a broader set of analyses in service of telling a coherent story. I wish it was the case that we could get work published that contained an incoherent set of results, because that would be a lot easier than being forced to tell a coherent story, but that would also not be good for broad usage of our science either- it is obtuse and difficult for regular people to parse as-is.

Feedback:
After a while, I decided that almost all of these "practices" ... "it depends" should be an option. 

Obviously, rounding down p values and the like is very bad (and dumb). But the stuff about statistical analyses, handling outliers, running various models, or including or not including insignificant results. It can depend on the theory you're testing, reviewer recommendations, and a whole bunch of other things. 

Research is a two-sided market. If I've got reviewers who recommend dropping a hypothesis or running a different analysis, I'm going to follow those recommendations, if they make sense.

Feedback: Interesting research! The vignettes were pretty representative of situations that researchers often face, although a few of them could have used more context. The role of replication was missing in the vignettes. Of course, you can’t include everything in your study, so I understand why this was omitted. My approach to research is to plan to conduct multiple studies from the outset. If something unexpected occurs in an earlier study, I’m transparent in my Results section about that unexpected result. In a subsequent study I attempt to replicate the unexpected result, often after making improvements to the methods I used in the earlier study. I often also report results multiple ways (e.g., we found x when careless participants were included, and y when careless participants were omitted; we found a when we included all planned covariates, and b when we omitted one or more planned covariates). In short, my view is that researchers must provide an honest and complete account of what they did. I would encourage researches to pivot when their study doesn’t go as planned (which happens a lot!!!); however, they should be clear in their research report that they have pivoted and they should consider conducting one or more follow-up studies in an effort to replicate and better understand any previous unexpected results.

Feedback: Some of these questions do not apply to my field and the kind of work that I do, because I have primarily collected large data sets that were intended from the outside to support the development of multiple papers, so it has never been the case that all results of all questions were reported in a single paper. And with the changes that have emerged in my field with regard to different statistical techniques, it is not a problem to try a different type of analysis if you learn that it is more appropriate to the data that you have. I do think that results should be reported precisely and that the methods section should explain what was actually done with the data. Whether one collects more data if he or she runs out of money is a different kind of issue and depends on what options might be available for that individual. But I have not had experience with preregistered studies, which seems more common in psychology. My background is sociology, even though I have been in a business school, and that practice has not been common or is very new. I am now retired, although still writing and publishing, but I am not doing the kind of quantitative work that I did at earlier stages of my career. And this took far longer than your estimates!

Feedback: This felt like a gotcha survey. You list a series of controversial practices without allowing for nuance. For example: Do you report null covariates? No. Because I don't report covariates. That is a note -- as described by good causal inference practice. Or, do you not report null results? Yes. Sometimes they aren't true null results because the CI is so large. So I would just be reporting noise. As the questionnaire is framed, I do not believe you are capturing the social norms you believe you are trying to capture. They are too broad of statements with minimal contextualization that leads individuals to state a social norm they precieve as correct, but does not reveal their prescribed social norm practice.

Feedback: The focus of this study is on the behavior of researchers, and their institutions, which is important.  However, I think the core problem lies in the behavior of journals and their editors.  They refuse to publish good research that shows null results.  This leads to organizational pressure to produce research with positive results which leads researchers to engage in questionable practices to get results.  This creates the academic equivalent of "fake news".

Feedback:
The study looks really interesting—you’ve summarised the reasons why I have minimised or avoided doing quantitative research in the last  3-4 years, found peace in qualitative research, and revised my academic career plans (I no longer aim for an associate professorship in such a hypocritical system). I also feel very happy about it, as I am under much less pressure to publish. If you plan to conduct cross-cultural comparisons, in the UK context you might benefit from exploring the Research Excellence Framework, research impact, and the pressure to secure external funding (to gain rights for teaching buy-out).

Good luck with your research!

Feedback: There were some that were hard to answer, like imputing data. I would impute items by computing my scale by averaging across items, but I wouldn't impute a scale. Or, like would I stop collecting after reaching significance. I always collect after reaching significance because I always use my whole budget. I think it was maybe worded in reverse, like we're supposed to keep collecting, but I had trouble evaluating that one. Similarly, maybe you should remove an outlier, including ones that help your hypothesis. So, some of them were hard to think about because it could be a good context. And I think I've internalized the horrible practice of not reporting all data or the Chrysallis Effect (e.g. Cortina, 2016). I take responsibility for that. But I really don't want to read through 10 pages of a paper just to find that nothing worked when I get to the results. That's rarely a contribution to my knowledge and rarely a good use of my time, frankly. There are so many reasons it might not have worked, like maybe it was a bad study or the sample size was too small. So I think that null results tell me less than significant results. That said, I've had conversations with other researchers at SIOP and three people will tell me the same thing- they can't get Schwartz's values scale to predict anything, or they can't measure OCB motives- those are two that come to mind. So, I think those have a place in dissertations so that other researchers won't waste their time trying to study that, but it's so hard to get even moderate impact articles published. What would the outlets be for these?

Feedback: The p rounding question seems poorly constructed to me. If the standard is p > .05 then rounding a value like p < .053 to exactly .05 does not make it significant. Feedback:
On the "no preference" option to the vignettes, note that this can mean indifference, might do both, or might do neither.  I selected it several times because there is no way I'd ever do either the a or b option.  Instead, when I don't get the results I predicted, I report that, unless it's so many unpredicted results that I clearly don't understand the phenomenon enough to report anything.  In which case, I conduct more studies until either I can a priori explain these results or otherwise reconcile them, or that research project goes in a desk drawer.   

Also, and you may have thought of this already, as someone who has been in the field for nearly 40 years, the norms of appropriate research conduct have changed A LOT.  Stuff that was encouraged 40 years ago is now becoming verboten.  I think you'll find older scholars like me saying they've done more of stuff that is now disapproved of than will younger scholars.

Appointment _4_TEXT: Full time research in an R&D agency
Feedback:
I'm senior enough that some practices have changed over my career. For example, it used to be the norm that one didn't report the exact p value, just whether it was above or below the criterion, so of course I have some publications for which that is what I did. Before the invention of supplementary material, it also was not uncommon only to put statistically significant results into a publication for space reasons, and there was no way to make other information available to readers. Things have changed.  I found myself wanting to explain this type of thing often in responding to the scenarios. 

There were several scenarios for which I could think of third alternatives, or nuances to the choices. For example, it can happen that after doing analysis A, I realized that there exists a different legitimate model that I had not previously understood, so I did B and reported that instead because it provided a clearer test of the concept. Not because it achieved a publishable result, but because it was more logical. I have also experienced instances in which a new statistical model was suggested by a reviewer, so we changed the analytic model between the initial submission and a revision to respond to the reviewer. 

There is an ethical argument in favour of a stopping rule (testing the data and stopping earlier than planned if the result emerges). Medical research uses this approach because it is unethical to deny a useful treatment once one knows about it. Even for organizational research (for which the consequences are not life-and-death), the continued use of resources including participant time and effort needs justification. This also had no way to be communicated as part of your scenarios.

Every researcher has a stack of papers they haven't had time to write. One chooses to spend time on those that are most likely to make a real contribution, which often are the reports that supported one's theory. Yes, sometimes this is suppressing null or negative results; but not always.

All of which is to say, I am not convinced that slavish devotion to an initially registered plan is the best route to good research. Gaming the system to make one's ideas look good (e.g., by suppressing variables from a report if they are not giving the desired result) is unacceptable; but the conduct and reporting of good research does involve nuanced choices.

Feedback: I would say that the publishing process encourages so many of these practices. Editors and reviewers often ask you to drop studies or DVs. I think the False Positive psych stuff says to present models with and without covariates (that's why I said I've done that). Honestly, people are cleaning up their acts but not fast enough. I think people hide behind NDAs not to share data. For the record, I think Juliana Schroeder is a terrible unethical researcher. What she has done crossed the line of fraud and should not be applauded. I have owned up to some bad previous behaviors that I no longer engage in (looking at data before it's done, having multiple DVs), which no longer fly. But I don't think others are quite there yet.

Feedback: Jack, you should have given space next to the questions! If you do not hide your practices (e.g., using a number of different statistical techniques) and report them when you submit, then you are NOT acting in an unethical manner. Also, Keppel's Design and Analysis recommends using a more stringent level of sig for assessing post-hoc hypotheses. Pre-registration expectations assume researchers don't learn anything while they are doing their research! Finally, your very last question is ambiguous! Which practices? One more thing: null results can be theoretically important!!!

Feedback:
Thank you for the opportunity to participate in this research.

This research focuses a lot on p-hacking. The scholarly community I work with often emphasises the size of effects reported beyond statistical significance, given that statistical significance is sample size dependent. Confidence intervals are much more informative than statistical significance levels, especially if you have sufficient statistical power for your analysis. Understanding the limitations around significance reporting could immunize scholars against the need to obsess about significance reporting. That said, perhaps attempts would be made to inflate effect sizes.

Feedback: Some of these issues are nuanced. For example, journals REQUIRE tightly focused papers, so you cannot always include all variables. In many studies you collect a large number of variables, and then have to pick a subset that reflects a narrowly focused topic. Sometimes that means writing several papers. Many researchers know that they shouldn't engage in certain practices, but journals require them. Reviewers will ask for different analyses and different hypotheses. They tell you to cut out nonsignificant results. They ask you to collect more data. Researchers are left with the choices of comply or find a different career. This is out of control and is damaging our science.

Feedback: I'm not sure if I completely understood all of the practices in this survey.  For example, my understanding is that a result is not significant if p = .05, which would mean writing p = .053 as p = .05 doesn't change the significance level of the result.  Also, in my doctoral program, I was taught to collect more data than your hypothesis includes because many results are null, so the extra data may help you find something interesting in your data that can be helpful for science, can lead to additional studies, or at the very least could be a future research idea for another paper.  I think the problem is less that researchers are trying to be unethical but the bigger problem is that many publications don't want to publish null results.  But null results are important and should be published because they tell us something about the theories we're testing, including boundary conditions!  If null results are rarely or never published, scientists are potentially running the same experiments over and over not knowing that they should expect null results or that someone else already found null results that would have informed the theory and helped scientists to make progress on understanding their phenomenon better.

Feedback: Very interesting survey! The first questions seemed like false dilemmas in some cases, e.g. the one on running multiple analyses. It seems like sometimes you might turn the data around in many ways, but publication usually only permits reporting one or two of these. And publication likewise does not favor including all the variables in a survey - sometimes you have to pick and choose to tell the story when drawing from a large dataset (though, it should not impact the results). Best of luck with the research!

Feedback:
1. I think I misunderstood the not reporting covariates. During the vignettes I thought it meant rerunning analyses without it then reporting those. But then for the second part of the study (my practices/others) I thought it was reporting the analyses that included the covariates, but not reporting the covariates (which is obviously much worse). Sorry for my confusion.
2. I think a lot of these practices are on a gradient. So it's hard to lump them in together.
3. Many of these practices are explicitly/implicitly asked for by reviewers/editors. 
4. I prefer transparency in reporting, so I might provide some of these additional details/analyses in online supplementary information. I prefer running with/without controls, for example, and report one in the main manuscript and the other in online supplementary materials.

Feedback: Interesting study, thanks for the invitation. I'd like to mention that some of the scenarios/questions could be interpreted in several ways, so be cautious in your interpretations. For example, when the first analysis doesn't reveal the expected results, you should run additional analyses to find out what was going on. But, you should be transparent about this! Similarly, omitting insignificant statistical control variables (ie covariates) could be reasonable in response to the limited word count in most journals. I have no issue with this, if you refer to an appendix with the full analysis or at least mention that the respective analyses did not yield different results than the one in the full text. What I try to illustrate with these examples is that there are grey areas which fall in between your scenarios and without the respective information in the vignette, respondents might answer to different situations. Anyways, I wish you the best of luck publishing your study!

Feedback: Cool study, nice title, but I do think social desirability bias may be an issue here. Even as I was trying to be perfectly honest, the "good moral answer" was too apparent in the scenarii. Also, most of the time, I'd judge a scenario I would have never gotten myself into, e.g., I generally delete missing data listwise, hence I'd never ask myself if I should report having replaced missing data or not. Hope my feedback helps, best of luck with this difficult topic. (P.S. : Glad I checked my spam folder today, otherwise I would have never known of your good work!)

Feedback:
It has not been possible for me to answer questions about my colleagues' practices.

Regarding pressure to publish, nowadays I believe there are some editorials that propose shortcuts to be able to publish more easily in journals that have high levels of impact in recognized indexes with generalized revision processes of one week. This facilitates the publishing process. In contrary,  trying to publish in prestigious journals is becoming a very competitive and complex task.

Feedback: The question regarding whether a person has published all the analysis needs to be a bit mor nuanced. Sometimes, I collect data with the view of publishing 3-4 papers from the dataset. So, I may have multiple analyses in mind when I am collecting data. As a result, I do not publish one paper with all the multiple ‘studies’ as a whole. I would publish three to four separate papers from one data set. So, I responded to this question with that aspect in mind.

Feedback:
Some of the scenarios are kind of vague, and leave room for interpretation. For example, with respect to not reporting non-significant covariates, I often leave them out but I disclose it in a footnote, mention whether inclusion/exclusion had any material effect on the pattern of results reported (changes in direction, significance, etc.), and often add "full" analyses with all covariates to appendices or online supplements. 

I think for some of these practices, the problem isn't doing them or not, it is disclosing what you did nor not.

Feedback: Interesting study. I remember a research book where the author said something like, "there is how people conduct research and there is how people are taught to conduct research." I believe the incentives/pressures of publication do lead to cutting corners that researchers are able to self-justify. I don't believe many researchers out and out fudge data, although that sometimes happens, but I am sure the incidents you are examining occur with some frequency, but who knows how often. That makes your study quite interesting.

Feedback:
Interesting and important project, wish you the best with this. 
One concern is that there are subtle nuances in many of the scenarios you depicted that may make a practice more or less appropriate.  Your method of inquiry does not capture this nuance.  I suspect you can address this in a discussion of results and/or limitations. 
Note I am a "macro" researcher and don't use many of the methods or theories described in your prompts, but I think your questions are universally applicable.

Feedback:
I believe there was an error in the survey flow; when responding to the "omitted nonsignificant covariates" prompt, I was presented with the "omitted key variables" prompt. Just to clarify, I responded to the "omitted nonsignificant covariates" prompt as I had already responded to the other.
Also, I am curious to read about your findings. This is an interesting study. For what it's worth, I do believe the "publish or perish" mentality has already killed science. Peer reviewers are trained to reward good stories and to punish the scientific process. We either want discussions of the complex decisions that went into generating final results or we don't--the way peer review works now, it is clear that we don't; we only say we do in methods classes. The transition from methods classes to real research was jarring for me and is, in large part, the reason I'm taking two additional years in my Ph.D. program.

Feedback:
The question about not reporting outcome variables that don't reach statistical significance was confusing to me since outcome variables are generally the dependent variable in a regression context.

The question of whether to collect more data when results lack statistical significance is interesting. And whether it makes sense to do so depends on whether your insignificant results are precise or imprecise? If you estimate a precise null effect, that is probably worth seeking to publish. But if you results are really noisy such that you cannot rule out relatively large positive or negative effects, your findings will have little interpretive value because they are under-powered. In general, having more data is a positive.

Feedback: Many of your vignettes leave out important information. E.g. will I report all findings? It can mean crosschecks or analyses just out of curiosity and for exploratory reasons. That I would say it totally usefull and it makes no sense to include it in a paper. It may also mean findings where in retrospect one finds that the method was not good. Again, why reporting something that makes no sense? Of course, you thought of intended findings that did not come out. But you did not ask for that. That, I am afraid, reduces the value of the findings a bit. We do not know exactly to what the answers rwäefer to.

Feedback: There were some vignettes that were a bit more nebulous (at least in our field). The one that stick out was about disclosing that the results are all encompassing even if other studies were run. Common practice, especially when developing our own experiments for a study, would be to pre-register these and subsequent preliminary studies. Everything is on OLR- however, NOT everything is discussed in the paper itself. Basically it would be cumbersome for a reader to read a "list" of preliminary studies, q-sorts, instrument tests, etc. So when I answered this question, technically I don't "write up" each study- although everything single associated study is pre-registered in the OLR and can be found that way (as the link is published with the paper).

Feedback: As with any case, additional information may be missing. For example, although a power analysis should be conducted before collecting data, if we overlook doing so, we may realize after getting a "close to significant" result, that we need to collect more data so that we have adequate power. Also, the prevailing recommendation is to drop control variables that are not significant when testing the hypotheses. These kinds of issues made it difficult to answer some of your questions.

Feedback:
This is a very interesting study. I understand that establishing percentages related to the use of third-party practices or our own is aimed at providing a quantitative foundation, but I found it quite difficult to accurately estimate these numbers. I believe it is important to consider scientific collaboration, as I have often worked with authors who engage in such practices, and I sometimes feel "forced" to adopt practices that make me uncomfortable or that I consider inadequate.

On one hand, I am currently less involved in scientific research, focusing more on academic management and teaching, having recently transitioned to this role in 2022. In this position, the pressure to publish is nearly nonexistent, except for my own desire to explore certain topics and studies. However, at the moment, I have very little time for traditional academic activities, including research.

On the other hand, prior to this transition, I spent the last eight years as a professor at a federal university in Brazil. In this context, we enjoy full job security (similar to tenure), with guaranteed career advancement requiring minimal effort. As a result, those who publish extensively typically do so for personal reasons, such as ego, rather than to advance their careers, since career progression is practically guaranteed with minimal effort. 
This situation is different from countries like the USA, where career advancement and achieving job security often depend on having a significant volume of scientific output. I believe this factor should be considered qualitatively in the analysis of the data and the study. Overall, I commend the authors for addressing such a relevant topic in today’s academic environment.

Feedback: I am in favor of transparently reported robustness checks, so I don't have an issue with things like running analyses with and without covariates or using different types of analyses, as long as everything is reported. I also think people sometimes run into unanticipated issues in analysis and I am fine with them using professional judgement and best practices to address those things, even if it is different than what they pre-registered (e.g., using a different model if the measurement model fails or assumptions are violated). Again, just needs to be reported. I also think sometimes hypotheses are really misaligned with theory and people come to realize this through the review process. I don't have an issue with changing hypotheses to be more theoretically-aligned (again, as long as this is transparently reported).

Feedback: I hope my results do not throw off your analysis. I am now an administrator, so, although I have published in this space, I am no longer as active of a researcher as I once was. This is important for your study because I believe the field is shifting in these practices. 20 years ago when I was doctoral student, these were acceptable practices, which I learned in my doctoral program and performed  based on reviewer and editor suggestions. I believe the field has become more aware of the problems of these practices, they are (I hope) no longer taught in doctoral programs, and I suspect no longer suggested by reviewers. In that regard, many scholars probably have performed these at some point in their career (as I have), but are likely no longer doing so. I want to comment, too, that my journey in learning how to do research was messy and I had to do a lot of trying different practices to learn. It is also extremely difficult to access quality data, so I think it is important to not point at the finger at the scholars necessarily, since some steps are a learning process. Rather, editors and reviewers might need to be asked these same questions about how many times they have denied null results or requested that scholars try different analyses. But I am hopeful for how the field is discussing these and putting structural practices in place that helps us have some guardrails (like the adoption of registered reports and submitting datasets). Good luck with your dissertation!

Feedback: You might be interested in looking at the work of Joel Michell (eg. Michell, J. (2008). Is psychometrics pathological science?. Measurement, 6(1-2), 7-24.) and then search for the completely absent rebuttals from the psychometrics panjandrums.  Also, there is a wider sociological point to consider - the social sciences are overwhelmingly populated by those with a left-wing bent, many of whom view themselves as activists rather than scholars. In common with intellectuals since Plato they consider it's fine to tell noble lies to useful idiots in pursuit of their political objectives.  Anyone who challenges the hegemony is struck down, but those who conform to the imposed myth are lauded and rewarded (https://www.nature.com/articles/479015a).

Feedback: Some of this is hard to answer. Some of the methodology questions don't necessarily express how I think about these scenarios. Yes, I think some of it is okay, so long as it is disclosed. If you don't find significance in regression testing, yet using another statistical tool, disclose it and try to explain why. If you remove outliers, they need to be disclosed and the pre-post analyses need to be presented. There's nothing wrong with it so long as there is transparency. Now rounding down a .053 should not be done, but having a p <.001 when it is .0003 is totally fine. That is expressing significance. Obviously, we can discuss the value of p-value over effect sizes and the like, but that's not the intent here.

Feedback: The situations you described are often not as black and white. If I get a p value of .054, I just report it as such. Not saying it is significant, but it is still valuable information. My general approach is just to be transparent about study design, analyses and results. Then readers can draw their own conclusions. Leaving out information or misreporting information is a black and white situation, and I find it simply wrong. Describing that you left out an outlier or control variable, and reporting the results with and without them, is fine with me.

Feedback: I thought this a very interesting survey, focusing on an important topic. Over the years I have moved away from quant research to qual research, partially as I am struggling with the integrity of what typically happens in quant research. An eye-opening moment was when a former colleague told me that they had published a high-level A*, of which the model collapsed when a theoretically relevant control variable would be added... That really changed my view on some of our current practices and made me question the stability of what we are building upon. Having said that, answering some of the survey questions was challenging, as things are not always black/white and right/wrong; the big problem is that we are not transparent enough about how we report these things in published articles (journals are starting to take steps to improve things though).

Feedback:
This study deals with a very serious issue but the field has major, truly and consistently major, methodological problems. You are thinking about p-values and the 5% level as something like the 10 commandments written in stone! People like me from a different field are fully aware of the statistics and econometrics literature on model and variable selection, model reduction methods, endogeneity, miss-specification, semi-parametric models and a whole lot more; I feel that the majority of the people in your field are not. Studies with 50 observations use 5% for significance and studies with 1500 observations do the same: this is raping of statistical theory and practice, makes no sense and should be abandoned for modern methods.

In your field and similar ones, people depend on what others say, usually considered authorities in theory but no way in empirical practice, and they never cite methodological papers outside the field of psychology and, in general, I was, and I am amazed at the inability of ill-trained people in statistics and econometrics to accept the obvious when it is shown to them.

Your work would greatly benefit if you actually point-out the methodological flaws in the field: the estimation problems that you deal with have been explored conclusively in econometrics and statistics and this is where people have to look for guidance.

Respectfully. 

Best of luck.

Feedback:
Questionnaire is longer than advertised. I hope that it doesn't happen but I suspect some people will abandon the survey because of this. A progress bar is needed.
One aspect which is completely overlooked in the questions is that research is often "reported" only in publications with strict word and table limits. Reporting of all results, all covariates, all levels of significance etc is desirable this is not always possible. I suspect that some of your answers (certainly mine did - and I have close to 200 publications) will reflect the inability to fully report and not the lack of desire to do so. We often collect far more variables that we can report on in papers. You may find that out when you try and publish your PhD work. What you have in your thesis has to be condensed. Those omissions do not reflect lack of research integrity. Don't confuse integrity will publishers requirements.

Feedback: I have published 50+ top tier empirical articles of the kind you are studying. There are many subtitles to my responses that were lost in the way a question was written. For example, it is possible to “analyze missing data” with dummy coding of demographic questions on which the researchers has data. So if I know gender, I can assess whether more men or women left a research question blank. Or with method of analysis, non results may stimulate alternative approaches. Like shifting from regression to discriminate analyses. Researchers are not omniscient. We learn with some degree of exploration. What is key is to disclose this in the limitations section of the paper.

Feedback: The Chartered Association of Business Schools UK list of 4* publications does not publish null results. They get desk rejected. CABS also does not rank open access journals it can take up to 5 years to publish 4*s. We cannot get our honest results published because null findings do not have the 'novelty'- a paper has to change/advance the field, but you cannot do this with pre-registered designs- the UK CABS 4* is surely resulting in fudged data- you cannot have incentives that reject honest researchers- fake data can provide the surprising and novel findings that are a requirement for 4* acceptance. But we are honest, and report ALL our nulls, even if we are getting rejections.  There is no way to progress because it takes years to get published. If you are honest about your nulls then the file drawer problem happens. It is now no longer possible to explicitly identify what the criteria are for acceptance or rejection in management journals because they no longer have shelf space. We write for free, review for free, and edit journals for free but the private publishers make millions. Of course unscrupulous behaviour happens. Publishing syndicates, and groups from different countries all cite each other. But the CABS 4*s desk reject null findings and actually say this in the rejection letters. Your research needs to bring change. Please highlight this issue. Nulls and replication studies need to also qualify for 4* journal publication.

Feedback:
One of the practices you asked about was omitting "studies or key variables" that were nonsignificant.
First of all, there was a typo related to this practice -- I think it showed up by mistake on the second page of questions about "not reporting outcome variables" that were nonsignificant.
Second, I found this practice hard to comment on because I think the field recognizes a big difference between omitting STUDIES vs. VARIABLES within studies. I believe omitting studies happens frequently and is perceived as not only acceptable and often desirable. I believe omitting variables within studies happens less often and is seen as less desirable.
Actually, at the slight risk of de-anonymizing myself, I once published a paper in which, during the course of the review process, in the interest of transparency my coauthors and I decided to include all the STUDIES we had run testing the hypothesis, along with an internal meta-analysis. This decision was very troubling to the associate editor and turned a promising R&R into a rejection (which we appealed multiple times before ultimately prevailing). After that experience, I firmly believe that the field deems it preferable to omit entire studies that didn't work (whether the field is correct or incorrect in this), and I will be doing that from now on and feeling minimal cognitive dissonance about it.

Feedback: The evaluation of methods is often difficult because of the large number of other factors that affect a decision. For instance, statistical significance may be set in some fields at a higher level (ie 0.10) or a higher level may be accepted for very small exploratory datasets. I usually work with large datasets so I prefer 0.05 or even 0.01. A significance level of 0.05 could be linked to a very small and not particularly meaningful difference. In terms of selecting statistical models, a model may not work for a large number of reasons, so there could be good reasons for rejecting it for a different model. For instance, a linear model that does not fit the data very well could be replaced with a non-linear model.

Feedback: I felt that the survey was too specific to research using experiments. In organisation science, a large proportion of researchers use observational data from government surveys, where many of the issues you asked about do not apply. I felt that your study had a narrow view of what organization researchers in industrial relations, sociology, economics do, beyond IO psychology.

Feedback: This is a neat study. On several of the vignettes, I was troubled because I could engage in some of the behaviors described, but with a different intention (that is ethical in my opinion). For example, it MAY be unethical to conduct several analyses, such as if someone only reports the significant ones. But it MAY be ethical to conducted several analyses to see if results triangulate across different analytical approaches. The anchors did not let me fully capture this nuance as to how the same research practice can be engaged in an ethical manner. So maybe that is on my for not answering the question as intended. But maybe it can inform future research on how the same research practices can have ethical or unethical implications depending on how they are enacted. Well wishes with your work!

Feedback: You are questions are too long. the options in your vignette are misleading. For instance, in exploratory analyses we are encouraged to try for different models and model fit. There is a whole scientific literature on outliers, and how to deal with them. There is a legitimate process of excluding them. In the rigorous disciplines, we run a gazillion robustness checks to demonstrate that an estimate of interest is not spurious. In one of your first vignette questions you have a critically important typo: You say an "outcome is not significant". What you meant, i think is an explanatory variable has no significant association with the outcome. As a senior scientist, I recommend you to re-design this experiment/survey. Warmest

Feedback:
I would note that most researchers over-collect variables because sometimes scales are unreliable, and back-up variables are useful to have. Unfortunately, journals/reviewers do not allow unlimited variables to be reported--- there is not enough space. Further, as long as you report all of the analyses you did, why not delve deeper if things look interesting from a theoretical standpoint? Again, it's about being transparent. And, if we round up/down according to conventions (e.g. journal uses 2 decimal points), what does it matter if we do so on an arbitrary p-value? 
All the best with your research.

Feedback: You are obviously immersed in NHST.  My own view is that we should go to pure registered reports. It is a fallacy to say an effect “exists” because it is p<.05 or that it doesn’t exist if not.  Posting data rather than preregistgering is what should confer confidence in the results. My objective in reporting is to do MANY analyses and report any and all that I thing would change the reader’s opinion about what the findings mean.  The whole idea is that you are trying to help the reader understand what you found, and if reasonable analyses seem to lead to different conclusions, report that.  That does NOT mean report everything because it is unhelpful to the reader.

Feedback: The types of behavior in your questionnaire perhaps differ with respect to the quality of journals research is submitted to. In higher quality journals, the tendency to conceal things may be lower due to better journal reviewing process and the higher reputation loss if unethical practice is discovered. Feedback: I am in a unique position of having spent time working in psychology departments and a management school. I have noticed a huge distinction between the two. Psychology is much further advanced with regards to advocating for open science practices and transferability in science, whereas management schools seem about 20 years behind. There is pressure to publish in both, but the prescriptive nature of what “counts” (eg FT50 list) and snooty attitudes around good v bad papers is far far worse in management. I was amazing that colleagues acted like I had three heads when I asked if preprinting papers was a thing, and it seemed to be driven by a fear that people would steal their work. The fear and pressure led to anti-science practices and I can understand why bad science still exists in management as scholars are under so much pressure. I hope the open science movement becomes more wide spread in management, but their predisposition to status and elitism means I doubt this will be a reality for a very long time. It’s a huge cultural issue.

Feedback: it is all more nuanced than how it is presented here. If you conduct first 20 experiments with students where every student has invented their own hypotheses, then  you are not going to report all of that and you will adapt your hypotheses later based on what you already know. But I don't think that is bad practice. That can be part of the scientific method. It is also more how natural scientists do it - they sometimes run experiments based on 'guesses' rather than inferred hypotheses. Also journals should enforce reporting all the figures and also null results so that the burden is not with the individual researcher. putting all the burden with the individual and ignoring the structures of the profession is not fair. (It's like demanding that every individual reduces their ecological footprint while companies can do everything to enforce you to use fossil fuels.)

Feedback: For some practices, additional information makes the difference. For example, whether a covariate is insignificant and should be included or not depends on the nature of the covariate, if it is a pre- or post-treatment control. It all depends on the causal identification strategy (backdoor-criterion) and every potential exclusion restriction must be theoretically reflected upon. I know it is difficult to include all "it depends" scenarios in a short survey, but it would help understanding the nature of bad practices in science. All the best for this interesting research of yours. Looking forward to learning more about its findings in the future.

Feedback: Some of the scenarios were difficult to answer given that I do not know the data enough. I would never engage in fraudulent behavior, but sometimes there are good reasons to change analyses. In addition, the page limits of some of the journals do not allow for too many analyses. So even if we have conducted several analyses for robustness they might not be possible to report in the actual submission. However, they might be used in (when that is allowed) a supplementary appendix (e.g. online appendix) or they might be reported to the reviewers but not in the actual submission. this is because the paper might become to complex if it has too many analyses.

Feedback:
The idea of "questionable research practices", especially in a survey like this one, seems to miss two important things. 1) Many of these pratices (reporting on only a subset of analyses, for example) are a requirement of a publication format which is short and "storytelling-driven", and 2) many of these practices (switching between various analyses) may be productive of misguided depending on the context. 

There are many instances when removing a few outliers, adding some more respondents, removing covariates can be useful, for some specific purposes. Exploratory analyses are an integral part of research practices, even though the current publication landscape seems to exclude them.

Feedback: I think that the topic "scientific misconduct" is a very important topic. I actually collaborated on a review on the topic (that was never finished, though). However, I think that for some of the questions the answers you get will not be the ones you actually intend to get. For instance, the question on whether a researcher has switched to another statistical procedure when a test was not significant: You may have conceptualized it as a way to gauge scientific misbehavior. However, there are cases where the switch to another statistical test is actually warranted. In some cases you may find out after you have gathered your data and conducted the originally intended test that the assumptions for the use of the test are violated in your data and you have switched to another test. This is what happened to me and why I have answered with "yes". Similarly, "Deciding to exclude data points after first checking the impact on statistical significance" may be scientific misconduct if you exclude the data point, because it makes the test significant. However, it may be an actual outlier that should be removed. Although I have removed data points that were influential after seeing that the original test with the outlier was not significant, I did not do this because it made my results significant, but because the data point was a probable outlier. Also, in such a case, I always report the results both with and without the outlier and I always address this in the discussion. These are only two examples, but there were other instances where you can find legimitate reasons for doing something (i.e. not scientific misbehavior), but participants cannot articulate them and have to do it here (which they might not do, because it takes time that they do not have).

Feedback: I think that a lot of questionable research practices were common in the past (in particular hypothesizing after the results are known, HARKING was common in a research group I joined 10 years ago. This was taught to younger researchers.). It think that open science practices are really helpful. I can now pre-register hypotheses. I can report more exploratory analyses on OSF and I can add a lot in the supplementary analyses. I recently had to review a manuscript where everything failed (no pre-registered hypothesis was supported), but this also led to interesting ideas, I reviewed it favorably. As long as there is so much pressure and a tough competition, some people will always try to cheat (see the Harvard professor who fabricated data). A day has 24h for everyone, and an output too great with great data makes me suspicous...

Feedback: Sometimes the two options on the continuum did not sufficiently describe the available options in the respective case. For example, using imputation is fine in my opinion (given the necessary preconditions) but you should always be transparent about it and also run an analysis without imputation to be able to compare the results etc. Same with covariates (= control variables), there is a whole literature on them that even suggest running analyses with and without them and reporting both. So, I don't think it per se a QRP, not being transparent and not reporting it, is the problem. There are a few more scenarios where I would have liked to explain myself a little bit. You can probably not change it, but maybe you can add a text box to each scenario next time that lets people write a few words.

Feedback: some of the questions did not make sense. mathematically, p = .013 IS correctly rounded down to p = .013 and p = .054 IS correctly rounded down to p = .05; however, this does not matter as p = .01 is not p < .01 and -  more importantly - p = .05 is NOT significant as it is not p < .05. So this form of rounding is both correct and does not change anything. it would be problematic to round p = .05 down to p < .05. Similar goes for some of the questions which were either black or white. I could report some analyses in the paper only, but still put the other analyses in an online supplement. I had huge difficulties answering the questions because such options are not considered, although they are common practice in the field.

Feedback:
Interesting study. Sometimes the vignettes/scenarios and then questions about questionable practices were a bit too broad. When asked if I did something, my reaction was often "not exactly in the way you describe it, but something like that". 
And some of the "questionable practices" can be treated in different ways. For instance, I have had situations where I collected data on extra measures that I did not include into a paper, not because results were or were not significant but because I realized a-posteriori that this specific variable did not add any value to the paper/story/literature or because it overlapped too much with another variable already in the paper. 
Or sometime I would not include stuff in the main results of the paper, but I would include them in an online supplement (often with a footnote in the paper) - that way it's transparent to readers. For me that's good science and not questionable. It's the best of both worlds: Transparency but without harming your paper by throwing in extra measures that hurt your story and make the paper unfocused.

Feedback: I felt like some of the questions about changing analyses or not reporting null results were unfair because of pressures more external related to things like page limits and the knowledge that null results as the main finding of a paper just do not get published unless they are highly salient and spark some  sort of controversy in the field. I absolutely withhold null results when they would put me over page limits and/or when that is all is found in my whole study. Why waste my time putting together a paper when there is a 0% chance it will be published?

Feedback: I found questions regarding outliers difficult to answer.  There are statistical tests for the presence of outliers, and I was taught that observations that are outliers lead to a violation of the OLS assumptions and, therefore, should be excluded from the analysis.  However, these tests for outliers occur before tests of statistical significance, and not because a result is found to not be statistically significant.  I think it's possible that researchers may find an insignificant result, for which the unexpected outcome prompts a return to the proper process of testing for outliers, which should -- in its purest approach -- occur first.

Feedback: The questions on the practices from members of the field are tricky because the approval or disapproval is not clear whether member of the field actually do it - I know the next question is should they, but the point I am making is generally I'd say the "field" suggests not to do those things, yet the same people that say not to do them still do. So there are instances where I answered the questions with somewhat approve because they do the practices while holding the belief that they should not. Even some that I very well could have submitted "strongly disapprove" answers for were tempered by this situation. Most of the somewhat approve would have at least somewhat disapprove if it was solely based on beliefs. But because behaviors are quite contradictory, I answered with more approval. I do not feel like it is just a few bad actors behaving against their beliefs (see O’Boyle, Banks, Gonzalez-Mulé's 2017 JoM), thus my answers were more indicate a higher level of approval based on actions that speak louder than words (of belief in practices). It is all very relevant to the publication pressure scale. Basically, I answered the approval questions under the belief that "others" should not do these things, however, because they have and successfully published, I'll follow their path to publication which includes doing these practices - though generally they shouldn't be use (at least not commonly, frequently or widespread). Some of the practices are frowned upon of old, but new science is more neutral on because of new techniques/approaches.

Feedback: For some of A v. B scenarios, another plausible option could be a mix of A and B (or both in full). In particular, I may be inclined to report the null findings, but if I also found some interesting findings as supplemental analyses, I believe it would be appropriate to report both as long as I'm clear about the former being a priori and the latter being supplemental/exploratory. Additionally, my understanding about imputing data or removal of outliers is that it is appropriate to report the results in "raw" form and with any modifications such as outliers removed, imputed responses, transformations, etc. So, the researcher can be honest and transparent about findings, but report the results both ways with proper justification about reporting the results. Furthermore, some studies may have multiple "parts" that could be published separately - this is often the case with grants and multi-study dissertations. In such instances, multiple publications can come from the papers, and often the most compelling findings are prioritized first. To be very clear, I'm glad that our field is taking ethical research practices seriously. However, I think it may be important to consider that some of the A v. B options might have an ethical and transparent "middle ground", such as the examples above.

Feedback: Great topic, and nice questions. Congratulation. I wish you good luck! One minor comment concerning insignificant covariates in a model. Only significant covariates are included when the backstep (or forward step) method is used in a regression model. So, I would mention all the covariates in the publication but keep only significant effects in the final model. And, of course, I would keep all control variables regardless of their significance, as well :). It was challenging to choose between the provided options "keep in model" vs. "not mention in a publication."

You also ask about percentages of colleagues that do not abide by such rules: I personally couldn't care less, except that my colleagues need to be transparant.

Feedback: I mostly preregister and replicate my studies, making adjustments between them. Sometimes I run an exploratory study, explore the data, preregister, and run another study. Not all of my early studies end up in the final manuscript, for various reasons. Additionally, sometimes reviewers will "suggest" narrowing a manuscript's focus, or separating out a hypothesis into multiple for clarity or to make it easier on the reader, which influences what and how gets reported; or we'll include exploratory variables in a study that don't end up fitting the manuscript, sometimes because they don't turn out. In these cases, we either report all measures that were included in the study in a list or at the least we provide the study materials, data, and code through a link to OSF so people can see what we did that did not make it into the actual text. (e.g., exploratory analyses).

Feedback:
Some of the decisions were contingent on factors not mentioned.  Examples:
1) When there is a large dataset with many variables, there is absolutely multiple analyses being done, not all of which are directly related to any one project.  There may be control variables included but other variables not included.
2) Small datasets may be because of pressures on time, money and availability of subjects.  It may be necessary to expand the dataset to get results because the number was too small.
3) I like to use various analysis techniques and usually plan ahead what I will do and in what order.  I am not always sure which is the most appropriate and the results can inform my decision making.  Also, why would you waste your time and move to more sophisticated techniques if preliminary tests using more basic approaches show there is nothing there?

My very strong positions regarding the topic of your research:
1) Do not misrepresent what you have done.
2) Do not present false results (due to manipulation, misrepresentation).  This leads to bad science, inappropriate prescriptions and a boatload of other bad things
30 Do not sacrifice appropriate research processes and good science to benefit yourself.

We all know that not all research goes as we hope or expect.  In sports the phrase is 'that's why the play the game'.  We need to maintain the integrity of the process.  That means, in part, doing what we can to stop selfish dishonest researchers who find a way to rationalize their actions for their personal gain.

Feedback:
I appreciate these questions.  If there were open-ended responses I would have noted a few things for many of them:

1) I've been doing research for 35 years.  Norms have changed a lot. So questions about "have you ever" cover years in which bad practices were common.  I've changed my own standards a lot -- principally in the last 15 years.  I would have answered many questions differently if you asked me about my work over the last 15 years.  

2) I also have the benefit of running online experiments and with a lot of resources.  Thus, I replicate the heck out of everything. Many of the shady practices described aren't applicable in most of my studies.  I don't do costly, time consuming field studies where I have to "find something" in my data.  Instead, I develop reliable experimental paradigms and draw on them multiple times.  (This raises a question not raised in your questions -- the oversampling of stimuli that "work".  They yield replication reliably; but to report them properly requires being cautious about generalization to other stimuli....)

3) If I had space to give a more nuanced answer for most questions, I would say that I would disclose data choices that are being made and deviations from pre-registration.  I'd run a lot of robustness checks to show that choices are not self-serving.  And I'd use a supplement to provide a complete picture of these choices.  For example, if coviarates are not significant and dropped, I'd report that they were excluded from the analysis and include them in a regression in the supplement.  I'm assuming the nonsignificant covariates are pre-registered, are not of theoretical interest, and that there presence or absence do not alter the conclusion of the focal tests.

Feedback:
Some of the vignettes were difficult to answer because the answers were dependent on having completed the practice in the vignette, which I would not have done to begin with (e.g., checking for significance after every 5 people - I wouldn't check for significance until data collection was complete, so the responses then become fairly irrelevant). 

I also found it difficult to estimate proportions of people who engage in different practices. Ideally, I hope most people are well-informed about open science and best practices, but I am not sure about the broader population of researchers. 

Good luck with your dissertation!

Feedback:
Some of the scenario questions had limited answer options - I often would say "neither of those" (then I went either for not answering or the middle option).  E.g. when something that was well expected fails to show, I absolutely would explore deeper why this was the case, it is very interesting! Or when something unexpected but grandiose suddenly shows - obviously I would explore this. But in both cases I would obviously not aim to publish those findings, based on a one study result, as this would not be trustworthy, without further studies and data collections. I think exploration is absolutely essential, and can be the starting point for further studies.

As for the "not all analyses reported" - of course there are way more analyses often going on than reported, i.e. pre condition checks, robustness checks. I would not want to publish shoddy results! But journals word counts do often not allow for reporting those, and overlong appendices are not welcomed either (its great if you can show the same thing with a different method).  I tend to report the simplest analysis possible, and of course I conduct robustness checks. 

This is very much about researchers own practices. But it gets a lot more complicated in collaboration projects, where e.g. analyses are done by a coauthor. How can all these things be checked then.

Feedback: Some of the questions about practices do not include other factors. For example, journals have a limited number of pages and that's one reason to not report variables that are not significant when I have to economize the words to fit the page limits. Another factor is that our research questions may change during the data collection and analysis process, changing the hypothesis and other aspects of the study. The way the questions were asked in this study does not consider these and other issues. Anyway, I think the study is very interesting and hope you get a good picture about the publishing pressure and climate. My view is that we, in academia, created a "business" that gives incentives for researchers to cheat and be dishonest to keep up with the reputation of schools and universities. good luck!
