Feedback:
Many of the vignettes have obvious third options, so they set up a false dichotomy.  For some, more information would really be needed--Is it an exploratory analysis from the get go?  Was the study preregistered?  Those make a difference in what should be reported.  But if I'm just playing with data and see something interesting and then develop a study out of it, is there really a way to report that?  And some things are practical choices.  If I have 30 variables and a journal has a 10 page limit, I simply cannot focus on everything.  So a "pure" standard is simply not possible to maintain in my field. 

Other questions are leading; but, I'm not sure if that was the intent (for example, the end questions included "often", "sometimes", "never", etc., which make the answer choice clear--people fail and are, generally, inconsistent with what they believe they should do.

Feedback:
Preregistration will not solve the replicability crisis. The pressure to publish, combined with the disproportionate increase in bureaucratic tasks (self-monitoring, self-evaluation) is becoming a scourge!!
Some of the questionable research practices, in our field, are the norm and not the exception. I discovered that they were "questionable" only after reading the post "replicability crisis" articles (from 2011 onwards). This has partly changed my behavior and I am also happy about it!!
Many "exploratory" researches are published as "confirmatory" because of the prevalence of a neo-positivist mentality. No journal would ever publish an article with "purely exploratory" results. They would ask me to do a second "confirmatory" study.
The first article I tried to publish was a "replication" and was rejected. One reason for the rejection was that it was a replication and not original enough.
I have tried to publish replications other times and always at least some referee or editor said that the work was not original, but "just" a replication.
Some reasons behind the difficulty in replicating studies are not related to questionable research practices, in my opinion, but:
- lack of good theories
- intrinsic weakness of the psychological data
I suggest reading, concerning this second point, Frazier et al., 2004. Testing moderator and mediator effects in Counseling Psychology Research; Blanton and Jaccard, 2006. Arbitrary Metrics.
- elusiveness of the phenomena investigated
I suggest reading, with respect to the last point, the article by Mayrhofer et al., 2024. The quantitative paradigm and the nature of the human mind. The replication crisis an an epistemological crisis of quantitative psychology in view of the ontic nature of the psyche.

Feedback:
Difficult to assess what others do, honestly I have no idea. But based on my experiences I assume people are honest. 
Regarding the change in analyses, I indicated it could be ok, because usually it is better to cross-validate analyses techniques (the "universe" of analyses is important). If someone analyzes data in different ways, I think it is a good thing, to check that your result does not come from the one analytic strategy you had planned (but ideally you would plan multiple analyses).

Feedback: Where to start. I commend that you are investigating these issues but there are, in my mind, some substantial issues. First, there is a distinct difference between what a researcher intends to produce and the product that is published. If a reviewer asks me to remove n.s. variables or DVs and I do, is that the same as excluding them in the first place? I think your investigation would be improved by clarifying whether you are talking about initial submissions of work or revisions based on feedback as that is an important dimensions and reality of the peer review process. Additionally, defining what is meant by covariates: is that any variable I collected? I don't report analyses (or even run tests) with many covariates that I routinely collect. Also, and I'm sure this wasn't intentional, a tone of dismissal and pearl-clutching in many of the questions about research practices especially in the vignettes so I decided to skip those as they were impossible to answer. In my mind, the supplemental or post-hoc analysis section is there for most of the situations discussed. Lastly, there was some discussion about switching 'analysis techniques'.. I read this as switching between different reasonable regression options to see if results are different, which I think many people do as a means to better understand their results. But maybe you meant something like switching between a one-tailed and two-tailed test just to get the p-value down to <.05? Good luck!

Feedback: Thank you for the survey. I found that many of the options did not quite reflect the nuances that I wanted to express. I review a lot of papers for journals and awards committees. I think that often the reason for poor practices is a lack of knowledge, experience, or guidance; for example, changes need to be made because. For example, because a research student did not know enough about the analysis and the supervisors or advisors also did not know or did not provide sufficient oversight initially. Also, when adjustments or changes are made, there is a big difference between making a change that is then reported in the paper versus not reported. Finally, some changes may end up being made after a paper is rejected so that the story can be told more coherently and concisely (especially of research students’ work as it is further refined after the award of the degree) but there was no room to comment about this earlier in the survey.

Feedback: Your survey lacked the ability to select "OTHER." A forced choice, as you superimposed here, assumes I want to pick what I did, which was NOT the case. There are other alternatives that would have been much better than the options provided --in certain cases. It does "irk" me when researchers are unwilling to do their homework i.e., analyze the "other" options, combining quant/qual methods. Yes, this means MORE work for the scholar, but it provides infinitively more detailed and granular insight at the end of the day. If you care about this topic, you should have provided open box options for each question or provided an "other" choice. You need to see what those better options might be, if you really want to learn from this study! You'll never know now what the best option may have been, as you only have what you already know (your own forced choices).

Feedback: I didn't answer the question about whether all analyses are/should be published. The reason is that journal page limitations often prevent literally all analyses in a project from being published. There is inevitably some picking and choosing. But these judgments can be made with honesty and integrity. So I don't think the survey question was well-posed. There were a few other questions I didn't answer because they were ambiguous or not well posed.

Feedback:
Some of the early questions are misleading, as some of the "practices" that you name are things that can be requested by reviewers, leaving little choice to authors, such as: (a) delete the predictors and outcomes that are not significant; (b) adjust the intro to modify hypotheses so that they fit with the results.  Other issues are just good practices. For instance, you can realize that the person who did some of the analyses before you forgot to check for multivariate outliers, forcing you to backtrack to redo things properly. Just like sometimes you realize that alternative, and even new, methods are better than those you plans. In terms of "covariates", best practices in research (base don statistics) is to avoid including unnecessary controls (as they introduce noise and reduce power), which means that preliminary analyses are required to select those. It would be silly to expect authors to report all stages of data cleaning and preliminary analyses. Modern research, when trying to explain something as complex as human beings, increasingly forces researchers (at least those with strong quantitative skills) to look at their data from multiple sides to find out what the data has to tell. Thinking that everything has to be determined a priori is stupid and unrealistic. This is why Artificial Intelligence and Machine Learning as now able to achieve a far greater success at predicting behaviors than psychological research does. We need to move past simplistic and useless T-testing, correlations, and linear regression to conduct good research. 

But more importantly, the worst and most harmful things that I have been asked to implement in my research have always been suggested by ignorant reviewers who feel legitimate to comments on things that they do not know. As an "established" researcher, I always respond quite clearly that I would not do that, trying to educate them as to why there suggestions are wrong (e.g., deleting participants who completed a single time point in a longitudinal project, which goes against everything we know about missing data handling in statistics). But it is a lot harder for younger folks to resist to that kind of pressure. So you correctly identified some problems, but you did miss one that I find critical: problems with the peer review process. The increasing pressure to publish means that people are now submitting a lot of article, and journals no longer cope very well with finding properly qualified assessors. Moreover, most good assessors typically serve on the editorial board of some great journals and work on their own research. This means that most of those doing reviews in other journals are those with time on their hands (those who do not do a lot of research, and should not be doing reviews). This is increasingly harmful.

Feedback: I think these are a bit pointless questions. Statistical significance is on many occasions misleading and in my field more and more scholars are opening to this fact. Especially in top journals and institutions. I answered these questions to the best of my ability but I would argue there are other more important considerations for this study than blind focus on P values. Please see the work of Deidre McCloskey on the subject.

Appointment _4_TEXT: Senior Scientist (retired faculty & retired PI on NIH grants) now working in cancer prevention training of mentors & fellows
Feedback: My role now is very different than when I was faculty at another institution and an active PI.  As retired faculty in a new role as Senior Scientist, I do not have the many, sometimes overwhelming, worries I had then.  I still work with active PIs, help them write NIH grants (and we get most of the ones we write), work on the resulting projects, analyses & papers.  As a PI I ran my own analyses & I work closely now w/the Educ Psychologist who runs our current analyses using SEM, multilevel modeling (which we consider routine). Our ethical bar is high on analyses & interpreting results. However, most of the time you evaluate many possible covariates, many key predictors, and there may be many outcome variables that are included in any one study.  Not all of the variables are included in any one paper; many "stories" can be told out of one large study w/sound theoretical frameworks that guided its development. Of course, "salami slicing", producing redundant papers w/the same variables is not ok, but in large studies w/large numbers of variables and longitudinal data, one cannot tell the many stories in one paper...there will be many papers and rightly so. I hope this explains some of my answers on not reporting all of the covariates or analyses done sometimes.

Feedback:
I found ambiguity in some stated practices . For example,
Reporting a set of results as the complete set of analyses when other analyses were also conducted.
It all depends. We would not include analyses that are not considered as appropriate or good enough. For example, in a RCT, someone may have done a simple t-test and later found it more appropriate to do regression with adjustment of baseline value. Only results from the later analysis should be reported because simple t-test is not considered as good enough. There is no option that allows me or others to express the concern of the stated practices.

There are other practices with a similar issue.

Also, some questions focus too much on statistical insignificance, without considering the clinical insignificance. Note that statistical significance does not necessary imply clinical significance and vice versa. There can be a good message for a clinically insignificant result (which can be statistically significant or insignificant) that informs the worth of reporting.  The decision is not entirely on statistical significance.

Feedback: The criticisms of empirical social science are well known.  Recent initiatives are in the right direction such as posting  data sets. But the vast majority of empirical social science is fake beginning with literature reviews. Of course empirical social science phenomena are complex. Data can rarely cover all sources of variation. And authors should be encouraged to always include a discussion of the unexplained variance highlighting potential theories that were left out or not considered in the original formlation of the studies.

Feedback: Many of these questions posit good research techniques as "bad," or are vague about their utility. Robustness checks should always be conducted, and different econometric methods can be justified based on the data - so if one method returns surprising results, it should be checked again. At the same time, there are model averaging techniques which can point out when co-variates should be dropped because they add nothing to the model. Re-running regressions without these variables is not a method of fraud, so long as the techniques are described in detail. Similarly, imputation can be used but it has to be stated up front.

Feedback:
Some of the questions on integrity were hard to answer. For instance, when I analyze data I try to understand what they tell me - not because I want the data to fit one theory, but because I realize that theories are themselves socially constructed and there is - in management - no such a theory that is universal (life e.g. in physics). This means that I play with the data not because I want to fake results or because I want to force the support of specific theory, but because sometimes the data go in a direction that is unexpected and this is good for science. Assuming there are no specific problems with the data themselves (flaws, or gross mistakes in the way they have been collected or measured), if the analysis points to a direction that I did not expect I see nothing wrong in changing my theory to accommodate a different story. After all, the theories in management are just good approximations to explain a context-bound behavior. 

Also, on the p-values, we can show p-values of 0.053 and to me, that is the statistical value in itself which I take as it is. The issue is not what we scholars think of 0.053, but what reviewers perceive (or are trained to perceive) as significant and so they might question the significance of a result because it is higher than 0.05 - which is of course statistically nonsense. If editors support these kinds of approaches to reading statistical results below or above a fixed threshold, then scholars are more prone to round the numbers. Some journals are luckily abandoning *** and asking scholars to report and comment on the numbers. Hopefully, the community will change its approach and take numbers for what they are, even if a theory is not fully supported - that is a result.

Feedback:
I found it very hard to make judgments about what others do. It's not something I generally discuss with others. 

There were definitely scenarios where I thought I would have taken a third option. 

My general feeling is that you can make all sorts of decisions in research so long as you report what you have done. Then it is up to the peer review process to say that choice was appropriate or inappropriate. Failing to report things like missing data imputation or removal of outliers is clearly problematic, but the actual practice of removing outliers, etc. may or may not be problematic in different circumstances. 

I felt like the issue of reporting was included in some but not all scenarios where I thought it was relevant. 

Interesting project. Good luck!

Feedback: Thank you for the opportunity to participate in this survey which explores various personal attitudes and behaviors. The range of statements presented was comprehensive, effectively prompting introspection regarding personal traits and reactions. However, I noticed that some statements could be interpreted in multiple ways due to their broad phrasing. It would be beneficial for future surveys to refine these items to ensure clarity and to avoid potential ambiguity. Additionally, the linear format was user-friendly, though integrating an optional comment box beside each statement could enhance the collection of nuanced responses. I appreciate the initiative to gather these insights and look forward to seeing how this data informs future psychological research.

Feedback:
The scenarios in the first part of the survey struck me as quite problematic (and so for many of them I just left it at the middle point) because more information is needed to make the choice. Since you neglected to offer the respondent an option along the lines of "I need more info" or "no response" you will have messy data because the midpoint of the scale will contain a combination of people who genuinely felt the midpoint view and people (like me) who thought it was a fatally flawed question and so elected not to respond.

Good luck with your study!

Feedback:
Too many specific determiners in the last questions. Very few things are "always" or "never" true. 

More importantly, p-values can only extremely rarely be "equal" to a specific value, and should never be reported as such. They need to be expressed as an inequality (e.g., p < .05) as opposed to an exact value (e.g., p = .05). Thus, even rounding down from .053 would not indicate a statistically significant effect, technically.

Feedback:
Many of the questions required more context that I was not able to give (due to the structure of the survey). For example, it can be okay to do further post analyses on your data as long as you acknowledge that in the subsequent paper. Collecting more data after initial findings is the basis of pre-testing so I acknowledged that practice as normal. These are the things that I acknowledged as being taught in grad school when that question was asked but I was not taught to “cut corners” or to manipulate results to twist the “findings”. Developing hypotheses after the fact often happens in the real world of research when one is dealing with secondary data. While not ideal, it happens quite often that one has a set of data and initial results and then must find theory to explain the findings (usually the opposite of a normal scientific approach). However, this becomes necessary because journals require that structure- as if all research starts with a priori hypothesizing followed by data collection, testing and discussion of findings. In the real world the process can be iterative and this can quite often happen during the review stage where reviewers are the ones that ask for further analysis, etc.
I needed context for the last (psychological) items as well. I answered based on generalizations for each items but in some specific cases the answer might not be so dichotomous (to be true vs false).

Feedback: There is a certain obsession with statistical significance in the organization science/psychology. We are, after all, just dealing with qualitative data that has been quantified. More interesting than p>.05 or not is the direction of the effect. I think .07 and even .09 in many instances could be interpreted as "significant".

Feedback: I appreciate the topic of this survey- however I was concerned that a)the survey already is set up in a biased manner by saying that it is about dubious practices; b) it completely fails to account for much of the usual research process: you have some broad hypotheses and then explore the data.  Sometimes you explore too many relationships to report all of them. Your Ho is very clear: people bias reporting towards significant findings, and suppress insignificant ones. Agreed- that is bad. However, on a lot of the questions - the answer would be: that depends (on the size of the sample, for example; on the range of methods used, etc). I felt the report was very preset in its conclusions.

Feedback: For some vignettes, I found myself not having enough information or saying, "it depends." For example, in my research, I sometimes include additional peripherally relevant variables to explore data and generate ideas for future research. However, I would not report them in a publication. That could be seen as omitting relevant data, but for me, it feels like a poor use of limited publishing space. So, some responses came from a space of "it depends" rather than endorsing whatever practice broadly.  I know this hard to do in brief vignettes, so I say this just as a general feedback :).

Feedback:
Much of the pressure to engage in poor methodological practice comes from reviewers and AEs during the review process. I try to push back on potential unethical suggestions but generally still concede to their comments. Where possible I still use best practices and use many footnotes to explain exceptions. 
I'm increasingly convinced that the entire publication process is fundamentally broken.

Feedback: The research scenarios described are overly simplistic. For instance, in some cases, data collected in the field may be imperfect and require cleaning to address outliers. I don’t view this as a methodological issue; in fact, including outliers in the sample can actually bias the results. Additionally, the notion of a rigid statistical threshold is inaccurate, as there is extensive literature discussing the nuances of their accuracy. Beyond that, this initiative is welcome. I am already a experienced researcher, but I definitely think that there is unnecessary pressure on publications and the quantity comes at the expense of quality. Well done!

Feedback: I believe that social sciences should not try and replicate what is seen as best practices of natural sciences. In a paper, we are trying to tell a story and show a scientific finding. To say that someone should stick with the first hypotheses they develop and throw away their data just because significance was not reached is a preposterous idea.  When Fleming discovered penicillin, do you think he went “better throw this shit away, this does not match my initial hypothesis”?

Feedback: In some of the initial questions on (a) and (b) there are another viable options than those included. For instance, why 0.05 as the threshold of p-values? A p-value is what it is. Sometimes, a pval<0.08 or 0.1 could be acceptable. It is also advisable to perform additional checks and robustness checks so a single test could not be enough. Finally, when variables are control variables and the omission does not change the results of target variables, they can be omitted (they are not part of the main issue).

Feedback:
I found some of these difficult to answer because it felt like the only reason for doing our work would be getting publication - when I am driven by a variety of things including justice 

for example, if I had a bunch of covariates that were not significant - I might return to the literature and see whether my findings were aligned with other work - this would determine my decision making rather than whether or not it would be published. I may also try different analytic approaches (modeling) as aligned with different ways of thinking about the data and if I had an opportunity to engage in another way of thinking about the phenomenon.

Feedback:
regarding pvalues and publishing nonsignificant results: this problem is largely due to journal editors who will not publish nonsignificant results. Also, I have been frequently told by them to remove nonsignificant effects (and change the story accordingly ) or rerun the analyses in a way that would provide "better" results, even in our so-called "top journals" (such as AMJ or OrgSience).
If we could publish good work regardless of significance, p-hacking and rounding off and omitting results would no longer pay off. Also, if journals would be more welcoming of Bayesian methods (which I am getting a lot of nagging about by ignorant reviewers), we wouldn't even need p-values and significance to begin with.
